This paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category as it discusses the implementation of spatial consistency in a channel simulator for next-generation mobile communication systems. It may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category as it discusses the simulation of channel impairments and variations for adaptive antenna algorithms or channel state feedback. Additionally, it may belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category as it discusses the generation of life-like samples of channel impulse responses (CIRs) that statistically match those measured in the real world. It may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category as it discusses the ability to train and deploy massive multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) and multi-user beamforming. Finally, it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it discusses the exploration of the ability to train and deploy massive MIMO and multi-user beamforming.
